WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:22.200
All right, well, I'm really excited to talk to you guys today about Shiny in production.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:28.040
But by way of introduction, I'm going to take a little diversion and take a look at an example

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:34.799
app that I've been working on, and we're going to use it to illustrate some of the principles

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:37.400
and tools we're going to talk about today.

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:40.119
This is not the example app.

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:43.320
That'd be a little weird.

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:48.439
I want to talk about cloud.rproject.org, or if you look in the CRAN mirror chooser, it's

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:50.360
called zero-cloud.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:56.599
This is a CRAN mirror that you may or may not know is run by RStudio.

00:00:56.599 --> 00:01:01.900
And it's hosted on Amazon AWS, so it's pretty fast from anywhere in the world.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:07.000
But the thing that makes this CRAN mirror interesting is that the download logs are

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.320
freely available to download, thanks to Hadley.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:16.480
This is what the data looks like, just a simple CSV file that you can download, and it tells

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:24.400
you every individual package that is downloaded from our servers, and an anonymized IP address.

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:30.120
So lots of people have done really interesting things with this data, and what I was interested

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:38.080
in is I just had this hunch that every public-facing website that I've ever set up that got a significant

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:44.279
amount of traffic always had just a few IP addresses that would act crazy.

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:50.080
Just download way too much of whatever it was that we're offering, not in a greedy way,

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:54.879
but in a totally WTF way, as you will see in a moment.

00:01:54.879 --> 00:01:59.919
And I was curious, does this happen on our CRAN mirror as well?

00:01:59.919 --> 00:02:02.879
Certainly it's a very, very popular service.

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:09.880
So I wrote this application called CRAN Whales, and I'll give you a look here.

00:02:20.639 --> 00:02:22.720
So this application is loading right now.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:27.080
It has two parameters that I want to focus on.

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:33.720
On the top left, you can pick a date that you're interested in, and then the top N downloaders.

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:41.360
So in this case, by default it shows the top six downloaders, the six most active IP addresses.

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.199
On the right here, you can see there's some summaries about how much total traffic there

00:02:46.199 --> 00:02:47.199
was.

00:02:47.199 --> 00:02:53.880
There's three terabytes of data downloaded on the 14th, and however many files were downloaded.

00:02:53.880 --> 00:03:01.520
And for all those IP addresses that we anonymized, there were 69,000 unique IP addresses.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:08.000
At the bottom here, there is a plot of the hourly activity for downloads, and you can

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.759
see that it kind of ebbs and flows during the day.

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:16.960
And that highlighted portion at the bottom, that is the fraction of the downloads that

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:20.960
the top six downloaders are responsible for.

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:25.360
70,000 downloaders, and six of them are doing that.

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:29.759
And depending on the day that you look at, it can vary quite widely.

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:32.759
The second tab will let us look at these whales.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:36.199
I'm calling them whales, the top downloaders.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:40.639
So you can see here, these are the top six, and the height of the bar represents the number

00:03:40.639 --> 00:03:42.080
of downloads that they made.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:49.820
So PowerfulArgali, these names are randomized, obviously, PowerfulArgali downloaded as much

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:52.080
as the next five people put together.

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:57.279
But ZealousRabbit is kind of a distant second here.

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:02.000
The next tab will show those same six downloaders, or we can change that number.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
We can look at, say, nine if we want to.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.740
But now we're looking at their downloads over time.

00:04:09.899 --> 00:04:12.580
So for each hour, how many downloads did they make?

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:19.339
And ZealousRabbit was pretty steady throughout the day, whereas StickyChinchilla...

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:20.339
I haven't seen these names.

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:21.339
They're different every day.

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:27.420
So StickyChinchilla just had kind of a burst in the middle of the day.

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:33.820
And finally, maybe the most interesting view is we have a detailed view where we can actually

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:36.660
look at the individual downloads of each of those users.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:41.739
So this is where I go, you know, what the hell is going on here?

00:04:41.739 --> 00:04:46.739
ZealousRabbit downloaded eight packages 72,000 times.

00:04:46.739 --> 00:04:47.739
Right?

00:04:47.739 --> 00:04:53.100
It's probably a Python script gone wrong.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:57.779
33.4 gigabytes downloaded.

00:04:57.779 --> 00:05:04.019
Please don't tweet that.

00:05:04.019 --> 00:05:10.179
Whereas StickyChinchilla looks like maybe they downloaded all of CRAN, 13,000 packages

00:05:10.179 --> 00:05:11.179
maybe.

00:05:11.179 --> 00:05:13.579
They downloaded the current version of CRAN, and then they said, oh, let's go back and

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:14.579
get some more.

00:05:14.579 --> 00:05:18.700
I'm not sure what happened there.

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:20.179
And then you have other ones that are...

00:05:20.179 --> 00:05:21.179
I'm just guessing here.

00:05:21.179 --> 00:05:22.179
Again, I haven't seen these.

00:05:22.179 --> 00:05:25.339
I probably should have looked before I came up here.

00:05:25.339 --> 00:05:26.339
What is this?

00:05:26.339 --> 00:05:32.940
I don't know.

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:35.820
So really weird stuff happening.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:39.339
Strange things are afoot on CRAN, and I'm...

00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:44.619
If you have any ideas, if you're running one of these scripts that are hammering us, well,

00:05:44.619 --> 00:05:45.619
number one, maybe stop.

00:05:45.619 --> 00:05:48.420
But also I would like to know what's going on.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:49.579
So why am I talking about this?

00:05:49.579 --> 00:05:52.459
Why am I showing this fun little example app?

00:05:52.459 --> 00:05:57.579
It's just an example, but there are things about this example that feel a lot like production

00:05:57.579 --> 00:05:58.660
shiny apps.

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:01.380
So it's a useful stand-in.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:04.420
Number one, this kind of app is very natural to build in shiny, right?

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:06.940
Kind of down the middle of what shiny is good for.

00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:10.940
You're visualizing data that is kind of like in a tidy format.

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:12.019
Super easy to build.

00:06:12.019 --> 00:06:18.019
Number two, a lot of production apps have data that is updated over time, often on a

00:06:18.019 --> 00:06:22.220
predictable schedule, and that's the case here, because the CRAN logs are dumped once

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:24.779
a day.

00:06:24.779 --> 00:06:27.980
Number three, there's significant computation happening.

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:33.500
When I first brought up that application, it took maybe eight or ten seconds to load.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:37.459
It's loading hundreds of megabytes of CSV data and then doing lots of grouping and filtering

00:06:37.459 --> 00:06:43.260
to do all the counting of individual downloaders.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.899
And mostly aggregated data is being shown here.

00:06:45.899 --> 00:06:52.100
We're talking about, you know, millions of rows of data, and we are doing various grouping

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:57.660
and counting to show, you know, simpler plots, and that's the case also with most production

00:06:58.339 --> 00:06:59.339
apps.

00:06:59.339 --> 00:07:02.339
You're looking at summaries of large amounts of data.

00:07:02.339 --> 00:07:07.859
Okay, so before we go any further, let's talk about what production even means.

00:07:07.859 --> 00:07:11.100
I mean, we throw around this word a lot, right?

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:16.459
And I define production here as there's software environments that are used and relied on by

00:07:16.459 --> 00:07:23.059
real users with real consequences if things go wrong, right?

00:07:23.059 --> 00:07:29.260
So real users, not developers and testers that, you know, they understand if something

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:30.260
goes down.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:33.540
We're talking about people who really need your stuff to work, and there are real stakes

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:35.260
and real consequences if things go down.

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:42.779
So the sort of antonym or some not production environments would be proof of concepts, prototypes,

00:07:42.779 --> 00:07:43.779
sandboxes.

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:47.380
These are places where you expect things to go wrong, and in some cases, like testing

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:50.540
and staging, you kind of want things to go wrong.

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:51.859
That is not the case with production.

00:07:51.899 --> 00:07:58.820
You're always having a good day if you find bugs and or have outages on production.

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:00.619
So I'm using the word software environments.

00:08:00.619 --> 00:08:01.980
What does that even mean?

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:08.540
Well, it really means the network hardware and software and your code, all of that together

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:10.899
when you make a deployment of a Shiny app.

00:08:10.899 --> 00:08:15.019
So this is just one example of what a production environment might look like.

00:08:15.019 --> 00:08:18.179
You've got RStudio Connect in the middle running your Shiny application.

00:08:18.179 --> 00:08:20.339
That could be Shiny server instead.

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:23.540
You have Nginx, which is just a web server sitting in front if you like.

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:25.100
Some people do that.

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:29.540
And this particular Shiny app is running on Connect, and it's connecting to an Oracle

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:31.940
database and a Spark cluster, say.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:37.479
So all that together, if that's being accessed by real users, that is your production environment.

00:08:37.479 --> 00:08:40.099
That whole thing is your production environment.

00:08:40.099 --> 00:08:47.260
And what we generally do if you're following best practices is you have an identical setup

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:48.659
for staging.

00:08:48.659 --> 00:08:52.140
You want it to match as closely as possible to what you're running in production.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:58.340
So you duplicate that entire stack so that when you are using staging, you're really

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:00.919
doing kind of like a dress rehearsal.

00:09:00.919 --> 00:09:06.619
And you want to find all the bugs and work them out in dress rehearsal before it's showtime.

00:09:06.619 --> 00:09:11.200
So that's what I mean by production environment.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:16.299
When we're running code in production, when we're running production environments, we

00:09:16.299 --> 00:09:17.659
have several goals.

00:09:17.659 --> 00:09:19.859
So first goal is to keep it up.

00:09:19.859 --> 00:09:25.500
We want to keep our production applications up and running.

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:28.099
Number two, we want to keep them safe.

00:09:28.099 --> 00:09:32.859
The data may be private, the functionality might be privileged, and the code might be

00:09:32.859 --> 00:09:33.859
proprietary.

00:09:33.859 --> 00:09:36.580
We want to keep all that safe from unauthorized access.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:38.179
Now, that may not be the case for you.

00:09:38.179 --> 00:09:42.500
Maybe you're dealing with all open data and your code is open source, but you still don't

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:45.020
want your server to get hacked, for example.

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:47.840
So we want to keep it safe.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:49.659
Number three, we want to keep it correct.

00:09:49.659 --> 00:09:52.979
We want our applications to be relatively free of bugs.

00:09:52.979 --> 00:09:55.900
We want them to give answers that are correct.

00:09:55.900 --> 00:10:02.979
So we want to be sure that we can verify that.

00:10:02.979 --> 00:10:05.619
And finally, we want to keep it snappy.

00:10:05.619 --> 00:10:11.340
When you're working individually with R on your own laptop, the performance might be

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.080
a little less important.

00:10:13.159 --> 00:10:17.799
But when you put an application into production, you are probably going to have multiple people

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:23.440
simultaneously using your code, which means performance is a much bigger concern than

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.039
it normally is.

00:10:25.039 --> 00:10:30.719
So we want to make sure that our applications run fast enough for the traffic that we expect

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:36.919
to get and have the ability to scale if we need to.

00:10:36.919 --> 00:10:43.359
Now, a question that I have heard many times in the last few years is, can Shiny be used

00:10:43.359 --> 00:10:45.599
for production?

00:10:45.599 --> 00:10:48.039
And my answer is, why do you keep asking me that?

00:10:48.039 --> 00:10:49.039
Of course.

00:10:49.039 --> 00:10:50.039
Yeah.

00:10:50.039 --> 00:10:52.880
So for years now, yes, you can use Shiny in production.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:57.400
People have been using Shiny in production, including RStudio and many, many of our customers.

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:02.479
Yes, it has always been possible to use Shiny in production.

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:06.719
That being said, we've worked really hard on the Shiny team and elsewhere in RStudio

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:10.760
to make the answer in 2019 more than possible.

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:14.320
We're trying to make it really easy to run Shiny apps in production.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:20.239
And I feel like that bar has been achieved, personally.

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:26.359
That being said, I feel like it wouldn't be in RStudio keynote if we didn't kind of tell

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:30.520
you about the limitations and the challenges to our own software.

00:11:30.559 --> 00:11:35.400
And in the case of Shiny in production, there are really three categories of challenges.

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:39.799
There are cultural, organizational, and technical challenges if you want to put Shiny apps into

00:11:39.799 --> 00:11:44.080
production.

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:50.400
So talking about cultural challenges first, Shiny apps are developed by R users.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:54.400
Well, I certainly hope so.

00:11:54.400 --> 00:11:58.200
R users, by and large, don't come from a software engineering background.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:01.559
I mean, some of us do, some of us don't.

00:12:01.559 --> 00:12:05.280
And if you don't come from that background, if you don't come from a background of deploying

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:10.440
production software, you may not even realize that you are dealing with a production situation.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.359
You may not think about the fact that people are going to be relying on this code to be

00:12:14.359 --> 00:12:16.599
running day after day.

00:12:16.599 --> 00:12:21.320
And even if you do know what the stakes are, if you realize what the stakes are, you may

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:27.679
not know what the best practices are for writing production applications and deploying

00:12:27.679 --> 00:12:31.159
them.

00:12:31.159 --> 00:12:36.619
And even if you do know what those best practices are, often people don't anticipate or budget

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:43.900
for the amount of time and effort it takes to productionize and follow those best practices.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:47.679
If it only takes you three weeks to create a Shiny app, and you're getting ready to deploy

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:52.280
it, and then now you realize that there's three more weeks of work to do the appropriate

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:58.359
automated testing, to do performance and scale testing, to think about security and do those

00:12:58.359 --> 00:13:03.119
kinds of reviews, it can be really tempting to just cut the corner and just push out to

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:08.320
production, especially if nobody's standing there kind of looking over your shoulder.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:14.140
And we have definitely seen people do that, and sometimes they pay the price.

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:20.659
And finally, our users, by and large, I think as a community, we're not a culture that prioritizes

00:13:20.659 --> 00:13:24.260
runtime efficiency as highly as other communities.

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:28.059
Like the other extreme would be like the C community.

00:13:28.059 --> 00:13:34.320
We're generally more interested in expressing ourselves quickly, iterating easily, having

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:41.239
expressive APIs, and while runtime efficiency is important, it is not the most important.

00:13:41.239 --> 00:13:46.640
And that can be a detriment when we start talking about production applications.

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:52.359
So those are all cultural challenges that we face.

00:13:52.359 --> 00:13:54.280
There are also organizational challenges.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:14:01.599
If you're working with an organization that has IT and upper management, they can be skeptical

00:14:01.599 --> 00:14:03.440
of deploying Shiny in production.

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:08.000
I hear this all the time from people that the data scientists want to build Shiny apps

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.239
and deploy them widely, but then IT and management stands in the way.

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:19.280
Now, IT departments just sort of inherently, their incentives drive them towards conservatism,

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:20.840
and I actually think that's appropriate.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:26.080
I worked in IT as my first job, so I have some sympathy here.

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:30.599
They're probably going to be skeptical at first of data scientists creating production

00:14:30.599 --> 00:14:31.599
applications.

00:14:31.599 --> 00:14:35.739
I mean, it's not, this is not something that they're used to, and there's definitely going

00:14:35.739 --> 00:14:39.380
to be a little bit of a credibility gap here.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:44.159
And of course, IT and upper management, they're always going to be skeptical of technologies

00:14:44.159 --> 00:14:49.900
they haven't heard of, and a couple of years ago, lots of IT departments that we talked

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.659
to didn't know what R was, much less Shiny.

00:14:52.659 --> 00:14:53.659
That's changed a lot now.

00:14:53.659 --> 00:14:58.219
I think way more of the conversations we have now, people come to us knowing about R and

00:14:58.219 --> 00:15:03.419
Shiny, but it's definitely something that's still to be overcome in some organizations.

00:15:03.419 --> 00:15:07.739
And elsewhere in the organization, if there's an engineering department, a software engineering

00:15:07.739 --> 00:15:09.940
department, they may not be on your side.

00:15:09.940 --> 00:15:14.140
This is something that they're used to doing, and now data scientists are coming in and

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:16.460
saying that they want to do these things too.

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:22.299
And they may be particularly biased against R, just having heard that it's a DSL for statistics,

00:15:22.299 --> 00:15:26.580
not a real programming language, which is one of my pet peeves when people say that

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:31.880
about R. I think that's sort of the opposite of the truth.

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:35.640
So those are organizational challenges that you may have to deal with if you're deploying

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:38.799
Shiny in production.

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:42.919
And finally, there are technical challenges, and these are my favorite kinds of challenges

00:15:42.919 --> 00:15:47.359
because they're the ones that I can do something about for you.

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:50.520
Now Shiny dramatically lowers the effort involved in creating a web app.

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:53.359
I hope that's not a controversial statement.

00:15:53.359 --> 00:15:58.039
We've made it very easy, but what we haven't done is made it any easier to do the other

00:15:58.039 --> 00:16:01.159
things that are involved besides creating your app that you still have to do before

00:16:01.159 --> 00:16:02.320
going to production.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:04.960
We haven't made it particularly easy to test Shiny apps.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:09.799
We haven't made it particularly easy to load test Shiny apps, and we haven't made it particularly

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:15.400
easy to profile and deploy Shiny apps until relatively recently.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:21.159
And finally, R can be slow, and it is single-threaded, meaning that an R process can only do one

00:16:21.159 --> 00:16:23.599
thing at any given moment.

00:16:23.599 --> 00:16:28.200
It has to finish whatever it's doing before it can do something else.

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:36.119
So the good news about these challenges is that we can and have done something about

00:16:36.119 --> 00:16:40.200
the effort involved in doing testing and profiling and deployment, which I'll talk about in a

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:47.599
moment, and about the slowness in 90-plus percent of the cases that I've seen, R's not

00:16:47.599 --> 00:16:53.599
the problem, and we'll talk about that as well.

00:16:53.599 --> 00:16:56.960
So the rest of this talk I'm going to be focusing on the actual tools and software that we've

00:16:56.960 --> 00:17:00.760
been working on to help make it easier to do Shiny in production.

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:03.000
And by the way, I probably should have said this up front.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:08.079
If you are coming from a setting where you are not building Shiny apps for production,

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:10.880
that does not mean that these things will not apply to you.

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:16.319
Even if you're not putting apps up that people are going to access from all over or whatever,

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:20.520
if you care about your app being correct and staying correct, if you care about performance,

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:25.359
these tools are still going to be relevant for you.

00:17:25.359 --> 00:17:29.079
A bunch of these tools I'm going to not talk about, and then other ones I'm going to focus

00:17:29.079 --> 00:17:30.079
on.

00:17:30.079 --> 00:17:34.199
So RStudio Connect, you're going to hear about plenty this week, but it is our way of serving

00:17:34.199 --> 00:17:36.280
Shiny with push-button deployment.

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:37.280
It's an incredible product.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.199
We're investing a lot in it.

00:17:39.199 --> 00:17:42.520
ShinyTest is an automated UI testing framework for Shiny.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:46.920
We did, Winston Chang did a talk on this at last year's RStudioConf, and you can download

00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:49.760
that video, and there's documentation here as well.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.119
That is now on CRAN, which it was not last year.

00:17:52.119 --> 00:17:57.560
I was planning to talk about that in my talk, but I had to cut it for time.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.880
What I am definitely going to talk about today is Shiny Load Test, which is load testing

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:05.599
for Shiny, which is more exciting than it sounds.

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:10.400
ProfViz is not new, but it is a profiler for R, and I think it's so important that I want

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:12.000
to emphasize it again today.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.160
So I'll be doing some demos there too.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:22.000
Plot Caching is a new feature that we've released in Shiny 1.2, which came out, I think, in

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:28.400
December, and we'll talk about that in a moment as well as a way of speeding up plots.

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:32.359
And one last thing that I will not be talking about today is Async, which is sort of a last

00:18:32.359 --> 00:18:38.920
resort technique when your Shiny applications have inherently slow portions, and I did a

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:41.119
talk about that last year at RStudioConf.

00:18:41.119 --> 00:18:46.760
Again, there's a video available, and there's a very, very detailed website at rstudio.github.io

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:48.680
slash promises.

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:52.619
Unlike every other piece of software I've ever written, I am asking you if you are interested

00:18:52.619 --> 00:18:54.880
in Async to read the documentation in order.

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:57.680
I have numbered the articles to kind of emphasize that.

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:00.640
If you go out of order, nothing is going to make sense.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:02.719
So Async is hard.

00:19:02.719 --> 00:19:04.280
That's why it's the last resort.

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:11.079
But if you need it, you really need it, and I encourage you to study carefully.

00:19:11.079 --> 00:19:15.000
So we'll be just focusing on these three areas today, Shiny Load Test, ProfViz, and Plot

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.959
Caching.

00:19:17.959 --> 00:19:21.839
Now we're going to look at these three tools through the lens of Cranwhales.

00:19:21.839 --> 00:19:27.160
Cranwhales was pretty slow, and I'm just picking some random numbers here to set a target for

00:19:27.160 --> 00:19:29.839
us just to give a for instance.

00:19:29.839 --> 00:19:36.040
So let's just say we want to support 100 concurrent users for this application, which would probably

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:40.400
be equivalent to an average app at a relatively large organization.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:46.359
And then, again, just picking numbers, let's just say we want to support this on one dedicated

00:19:46.359 --> 00:19:48.839
server with a 16-core CPU.

00:19:48.839 --> 00:19:54.359
In a lot of cases, you'd be running multiple servers just for redundancy, if nothing else.

00:19:54.359 --> 00:19:58.479
But in this case, just to keep it simple, let's say 100 users, 16-core CPU.

00:19:58.479 --> 00:20:05.040
So it'd be great if each of our processes could support between 10 and 20 concurrent

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:09.000
users, although we'll definitely, if it's more, great.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:15.719
But let's just start with 20 as a test, and we'll see what happens.

00:20:15.719 --> 00:20:20.839
So our overall high-level view of how we're going to test the performance of this app

00:20:20.839 --> 00:20:25.040
is we're going to start by using Shiny load test to see if this application is already

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:26.839
fast enough.

00:20:26.839 --> 00:20:30.760
If it's not fast enough, we'll use Profvis to see what is wrong with it, what's making

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:32.400
it slow.

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:36.239
And then the real work begins of optimizing and figuring out how do we make that slow

00:20:36.239 --> 00:20:38.800
part not slow anymore.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:42.239
The first and most common way I think that people should do it is to move the work out

00:20:42.239 --> 00:20:43.760
of Shiny.

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:45.760
Don't do the work when a user is sitting there waiting.

00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:47.160
Do the work ahead of time.

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:49.920
And especially don't do the same work for every user.

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:51.839
That's extremely wasteful.

00:20:51.839 --> 00:20:56.280
I see almost nobody doing this on their first try.

00:20:56.280 --> 00:21:01.079
Almost everybody just says, I have CSV data, I've got gigs of CSV data, I'm going to load

00:21:01.079 --> 00:21:03.920
it up into my Shiny app whenever someone connects.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:05.040
Why is this app slow?

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:07.239
So that's the reason.

00:21:07.239 --> 00:21:10.800
Number two, if you can, make the code faster.

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:17.719
There are things that you should avoid in R like mutating data frames in for loops.

00:21:17.719 --> 00:21:22.160
You should avoid text connections.

00:21:22.160 --> 00:21:27.920
You should avoid using the apply function to iterate over data frames.

00:21:27.920 --> 00:21:32.959
Sometimes you can find way, way faster ways of doing those things by vectorizing or using

00:21:32.959 --> 00:21:35.619
dplyr and things like that.

00:21:35.619 --> 00:21:37.199
Number three, sometimes you can cache.

00:21:37.199 --> 00:21:39.280
We're going to talk about that in a moment.

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:43.839
And then if you really can't do those other three things, then you turn to async, which

00:21:43.839 --> 00:21:48.560
is a whole other area of discussion.

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:50.400
And once you've done all that, then you repeat.

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:52.880
Then now you go back to Shiny load test and see if it's fast enough.

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:56.880
And if it's fast enough, then you're done.

00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:59.280
So we'll start by talking about Shiny load test.

00:21:59.280 --> 00:22:05.479
What Shiny load test does is it generates large amounts of realistic but synthetic traffic

00:22:05.479 --> 00:22:07.579
to your application.

00:22:07.579 --> 00:22:12.939
And it monitors how long it takes that traffic to run, and then we can analyze the latency.

00:22:12.939 --> 00:22:16.180
So step one is you have to have your app running somewhere.

00:22:16.180 --> 00:22:21.739
So you can run it locally, or you can run it on RStudio Connect or on a Shiny server.

00:22:21.739 --> 00:22:28.540
Number two, you use Shiny load test in a browser to record what an average user would do, just

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:30.260
whatever you think is representative.

00:22:30.260 --> 00:22:33.099
So click on whatever inputs you think a user would click on.

00:22:33.099 --> 00:22:37.359
Take as much time to think as you think an average user is going to take to think.

00:22:37.359 --> 00:22:41.959
And once you've done that recording, you can play back that recording with some level

00:22:41.959 --> 00:22:43.239
of concurrency.

00:22:43.239 --> 00:22:47.719
So instead of one user taking those actions, you can have as many users as you want doing

00:22:47.719 --> 00:22:50.680
those actions simultaneously.

00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:55.479
And then finally, we'll take the results of that step three playback, and we're going

00:22:55.479 --> 00:22:57.880
to analyze them in Shiny load test.

00:22:57.880 --> 00:22:59.959
We have a built-in reporting feature, which I'll show you.

00:22:59.959 --> 00:23:05.199
Or it's just a data frame of events, so you can do your own analysis if you like.

00:23:05.199 --> 00:23:06.939
So this is what that actually looks like.

00:23:07.939 --> 00:23:10.939
To run your Shiny app, we just call runAppLikeNormal.

00:23:10.939 --> 00:23:13.579
In this case, port 6104.

00:23:13.579 --> 00:23:18.500
And then we launch Shiny load test double colon record session in a separate R process

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:21.920
and just point it at wherever your Shiny app is running.

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:29.219
So that URL could be on Connect, it could be on Shiny Server Pro, or it could be local.

00:23:29.219 --> 00:23:33.140
Now that we have this recording, recording.log, say, is where it goes.

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:39.020
We use kind of a sub-command of Shiny load test called Shiny Cannon.

00:23:39.020 --> 00:23:44.300
And you give it this recording, and you give it a URL to pound on.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.979
And then you tell it how many simultaneous workers and how long do you want to run this

00:23:47.979 --> 00:23:48.979
test for.

00:23:48.979 --> 00:23:51.140
In this case, 20 workers for five minutes.

00:23:51.140 --> 00:23:55.459
And then it prints out a lot of log stuff as it goes to work.

00:23:55.459 --> 00:23:59.780
When it's finished, then you go back to R, you load Shiny load test, and you call load

00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:01.800
underscore runs to load the data.

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:05.380
That gives you a data frame that you can then pass to Shiny load test report.

00:24:05.380 --> 00:24:09.020
And when that runs, it gives you something like this.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:15.380
So it gives you a graphical static HTML file that gives you some indication of how long

00:24:15.380 --> 00:24:18.979
it's taking these sessions to succeed.

00:24:18.979 --> 00:24:27.160
In this particular case, what we're seeing is really, really bad performance.

00:24:27.319 --> 00:24:30.560
At n equals 20, we are in really bad shape.

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:38.239
So what you're looking at here is each row of this plot is a single simulated worker,

00:24:38.239 --> 00:24:40.459
a single simulated person.

00:24:40.459 --> 00:24:43.959
And the x-axis is time.

00:24:43.959 --> 00:24:48.760
The red blocks represent the time it's taking the home page to load.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:53.839
And then the blue blocks each represent a reactive operation.

00:24:53.839 --> 00:24:56.719
So you changed a tab, or you clicked on an input.

00:24:56.719 --> 00:25:00.239
You caused some kind of plot or something to be generated.

00:25:00.239 --> 00:25:01.880
And that's how long they had to wait.

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:07.000
And the spaces between the blue boxes are the user's think time, where they're just

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.079
looking at the screen.

00:25:09.079 --> 00:25:14.040
So you probably can't see the x-axis, which maybe is a good thing, because that last value

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:17.560
is 250 seconds.

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:24.160
So we are talking about something that, in an ideal situation, would take 45 seconds,

00:25:24.160 --> 00:25:27.800
or maybe 40 seconds, when n equals 1.

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:33.079
And when we get to n equals 20, it's taking five, six minutes to complete.

00:25:33.079 --> 00:25:35.560
So completely unacceptable.

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:38.000
This application is way too slow to support 20 users.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.000
So what do we do?

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.119
Well, we could just throw more R processes at it.

00:25:42.119 --> 00:25:43.719
That's always an option.

00:25:43.719 --> 00:25:50.079
And if we run out of processes on a server, we could throw more servers at it.

00:25:50.079 --> 00:25:52.119
You laugh, but at some point, that is the answer.

00:25:52.119 --> 00:25:53.640
I mean, Google doesn't run on one machine.

00:25:53.640 --> 00:25:55.000
It runs on thousands of machines.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.760
So we do always have the option of horizontal scaling.

00:25:57.760 --> 00:25:59.160
But what fun would that be?

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:02.959
So let's just make it fast.

00:26:02.959 --> 00:26:09.199
So the next step, and a step that everybody skips, is to use a profiler.

00:26:09.199 --> 00:26:11.800
When your app is slow, use a profiler.

00:26:11.800 --> 00:26:14.959
When your R code is slow, in general, use a profiler.

00:26:14.959 --> 00:26:16.280
Do not guess.

00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:17.800
Your intuition stinks.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:20.719
I don't even know you, but it stinks.

00:26:20.719 --> 00:26:23.199
I promise you.

00:26:23.199 --> 00:26:26.119
It's so easy to use profvis.

00:26:26.119 --> 00:26:28.079
All you have to do is go to RStudio.

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:37.599
And at the top here, there's a Profile menu.

00:26:37.599 --> 00:26:40.199
Start profiling.

00:26:40.199 --> 00:26:42.560
Run your app.

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:43.359
Wait patiently.

00:26:49.560 --> 00:26:51.560
I swear time moves slower when you're up here.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.280
Something interesting happened?

00:26:55.280 --> 00:26:56.520
Stop profiling.

00:26:56.520 --> 00:27:03.599
And that will generate a very intricate visualization

00:27:03.599 --> 00:27:07.000
of what was happening during that time that we were waiting.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:08.800
So that's all you have to do.

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:15.479
I have, in advance, prepared a profile.

00:27:15.479 --> 00:27:16.880
I don't know if you can see this.

00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:22.119
I'm not going to get too far into how to use profvis.

00:27:22.119 --> 00:27:23.479
Documentation is very good.

00:27:23.479 --> 00:27:26.160
But let me just say, once you learn how to read these graphs,

00:27:26.160 --> 00:27:27.520
the answers are right there in front of you.

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:28.199
It is so easy.

00:27:28.199 --> 00:27:31.319
There's no reason to guess what the time is being spent on.

00:27:31.319 --> 00:27:35.160
And what this visualization tells us, in this case,

00:27:35.160 --> 00:27:39.520
is that it's taking 6.3 seconds to read the CSV file alone.

00:27:39.520 --> 00:27:44.160
Just the parsing, 6.3 seconds, way too long.

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:47.719
When we're calculating our first output,

00:27:47.719 --> 00:27:49.719
which is all underscore hour, it's

00:27:49.719 --> 00:27:52.680
taking 620 milliseconds just filtering and aggregating

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:53.680
the data.

00:27:53.680 --> 00:27:55.260
And that's filtering and aggregating.

00:27:55.260 --> 00:27:57.180
That's going to be the same for every user who

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:58.599
accesses that day of data.

00:27:58.599 --> 00:28:00.479
And then the plotting, just for that one plot,

00:28:00.479 --> 00:28:03.280
is taking a third of a second.

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:05.520
So those are all pretty big numbers

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:07.920
when you're trying to put apps into production

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:10.719
for a lot of users.

00:28:10.719 --> 00:28:13.880
So as I said before, the most important optimization

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:16.439
that you should be thinking of as a Shiny author

00:28:16.439 --> 00:28:19.280
is to move your work to happen outside of Shiny.

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:21.199
Do work ahead of time.

00:28:21.199 --> 00:28:24.119
If performance matters, do it ahead of time.

00:28:24.119 --> 00:28:26.079
It's really tempting to load that raw data in,

00:28:26.079 --> 00:28:28.880
but you're going to pay the price performance-wise.

00:28:28.880 --> 00:28:32.119
So ahead of time, do as much filtering and summarizing

00:28:32.119 --> 00:28:33.119
as you can.

00:28:33.119 --> 00:28:35.280
And then when you save your data, instead of saving it

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:38.040
as CSV, save it as Feather files if it

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:41.359
is important for you to be able to read it quickly.

00:28:41.359 --> 00:28:44.479
Feather is incredibly quick to load data.

00:28:44.479 --> 00:28:46.319
It's a little bit slower, I think, than CSV

00:28:46.319 --> 00:28:47.780
if you're writing, but for reading,

00:28:47.780 --> 00:28:52.859
which is what we care about here, it's the best.

00:28:52.859 --> 00:28:54.939
If your data source changes over time,

00:28:54.939 --> 00:28:56.939
then you're not just going to be doing this once.

00:28:56.939 --> 00:28:59.380
You're not going to be the one sitting down and just

00:28:59.380 --> 00:29:02.219
running these filtering, summarizing, and then saving

00:29:02.219 --> 00:29:03.660
to Feather on your machine.

00:29:03.660 --> 00:29:06.500
You need it to happen on a schedule.

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.819
If that's you, then you can use RStudio Connect

00:29:08.819 --> 00:29:10.699
with scheduled R Markdown reports.

00:29:10.699 --> 00:29:12.579
That is a really excellent solution

00:29:12.579 --> 00:29:14.300
that has lots of benefits that I don't

00:29:14.300 --> 00:29:16.140
have time to get into now.

00:29:16.140 --> 00:29:18.099
If you don't have Connect or you're

00:29:18.099 --> 00:29:20.260
using open source Shiny server, you

00:29:20.260 --> 00:29:22.900
can also do something yourself with the Unix Utility

00:29:22.900 --> 00:29:23.859
Cron, for example.

00:29:23.859 --> 00:29:26.300
But any way you execute scheduled tasks,

00:29:26.300 --> 00:29:28.780
this is the way to do it.

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:31.219
And by the way, this sort of approach

00:29:31.219 --> 00:29:35.140
of preprocessing your data for downstream applications,

00:29:35.140 --> 00:29:39.020
you may know it by its acronym ETL, Extract, Transform, Load.

00:29:39.020 --> 00:29:42.060
And lots of organizations have entire departments

00:29:42.060 --> 00:29:43.180
devoted to this function.

00:29:43.219 --> 00:29:47.219
So if that's you, then maybe someone can do this for you.

00:29:47.219 --> 00:29:50.819
What I've done is I've modified Cranwhales

00:29:50.819 --> 00:29:52.260
to use this approach.

00:29:52.260 --> 00:29:55.819
And the repo for Cranwhales is rstudio slash cranwhales.

00:29:55.819 --> 00:29:57.660
And I've made a branch called ETL

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:00.859
that does some of the processing ahead of time.

00:30:00.859 --> 00:30:06.719
So if this is our original performance

00:30:06.719 --> 00:30:09.199
with the original version, this is

00:30:09.199 --> 00:30:12.819
what it looks like after just that one change.

00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:17.699
Our overall time to completion has gone from a max of 250

00:30:17.699 --> 00:30:20.619
and an average somewhere definitely north of 200

00:30:20.619 --> 00:30:24.219
down to, I don't know, 60 seconds, something like that.

00:30:24.219 --> 00:30:25.540
So a really big difference.

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:27.300
The size of each individual block

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:30.420
has not only gotten smaller, but also gotten more consistent.

00:30:30.420 --> 00:30:33.660
So we're seeing more predictable, more understandable

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:35.219
user wait times.

00:30:35.219 --> 00:30:38.300
And overall, we're looking a tremendous amount better.

00:30:38.300 --> 00:30:40.699
So I'm going to pause for a second and bring up.

00:30:40.699 --> 00:30:43.219
Those are just screenshots, but I'm going to bring up.

00:30:43.219 --> 00:30:48.420
This is the actual Shiny load test web page

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:51.219
that was generated.

00:30:51.219 --> 00:30:53.780
So this is that screen that we've been looking at.

00:30:53.780 --> 00:30:55.219
This is the visualization we've been looking at.

00:30:55.219 --> 00:30:58.780
And we can flip back and forth between these sync and ETL

00:30:58.780 --> 00:31:01.140
versions of the app.

00:31:01.140 --> 00:31:04.119
And this view shows all of the sessions

00:31:04.119 --> 00:31:07.900
that were run, sort of arranged tip to tip.

00:31:07.900 --> 00:31:11.979
But this actually all happened over five minutes.

00:31:11.979 --> 00:31:16.020
So this view shows those sessions

00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:20.939
running where the x-axis is actual elapsed wall time.

00:31:20.939 --> 00:31:29.219
So you can see here that these 20 simulated users did not

00:31:29.219 --> 00:31:30.500
finish very many sessions.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:33.459
Maybe each one finished three sessions or something

00:31:33.459 --> 00:31:34.900
like that.

00:31:34.900 --> 00:31:37.660
If we switch to the ETL branch, a lot more sessions

00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:38.540
are getting complete.

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:40.180
So a lot more work was able to be done

00:31:40.180 --> 00:31:41.459
because it was so much faster.

00:31:43.979 --> 00:31:46.939
There's also this event waterfall view.

00:31:46.939 --> 00:31:49.180
On the left hand side, we're basically

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:51.780
looking at the recording script that we generated when

00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:55.099
we kind of simulated being a user.

00:31:55.099 --> 00:31:57.180
That first line, you probably can't read it,

00:31:57.180 --> 00:31:58.979
says get home page.

00:31:58.979 --> 00:32:01.900
And then there are many lines, maybe a couple dozen lines,

00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:06.219
of retrieving JavaScript and CSS, which should be really fast

00:32:06.219 --> 00:32:07.540
and it is.

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:10.939
Everything from that kind of hump

00:32:10.939 --> 00:32:12.459
where they all go to the right down,

00:32:12.459 --> 00:32:15.140
those are all reactive operations.

00:32:15.140 --> 00:32:18.660
So that's the actual work of the application being done.

00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:22.300
And again, the x-axis here is time.

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:26.060
So in an ideal situation, if our app is super fast,

00:32:26.060 --> 00:32:27.859
these lines would drop straight down.

00:32:27.859 --> 00:32:29.660
They'd drop straight to the ground.

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:33.060
Instead, what we're seeing is as soon as they kind of finish

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:35.260
the loading of JavaScript and CSS,

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:37.219
these lines kick way out to the right,

00:32:37.219 --> 00:32:39.859
meaning that the user is waiting a long time to proceed

00:32:39.859 --> 00:32:42.739
from one step to the next.

00:32:42.739 --> 00:32:46.060
If we switch to the ETL branch, these lines are much straighter.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:49.020
So you can see not only are they straighter,

00:32:49.020 --> 00:32:51.540
but they're sort of smoother and more consistent.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:55.060
So each of the individual sessions

00:32:55.060 --> 00:32:58.380
are behaving pretty much the same way.

00:32:58.380 --> 00:33:01.060
I won't get too far into the other options available here,

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:03.459
but there are a bunch of other things you can look at.

00:33:03.459 --> 00:33:06.739
This one shows the amount of latency

00:33:06.739 --> 00:33:09.140
for each home page request.

00:33:09.140 --> 00:33:13.739
And the top facet here is the original version,

00:33:13.739 --> 00:33:15.380
and then down here is the ETL version.

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:16.939
So you can see a huge difference.

00:33:16.939 --> 00:33:19.939
And then the same thing for WebSocket traffic, which really

00:33:19.939 --> 00:33:21.780
means reactive computation.

00:33:21.780 --> 00:33:24.619
So reactive computations took a really long time here.

00:33:24.619 --> 00:33:26.780
And then for the new improved version, way better.

00:33:34.459 --> 00:33:36.060
So let's just summarize how we did.

00:33:36.060 --> 00:33:38.939
So ETL, clearly, much faster.

00:33:38.939 --> 00:33:40.420
What we learned from that report was

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:41.979
that the median session duration has

00:33:41.979 --> 00:33:44.780
dropped from 210 seconds to about 50 seconds,

00:33:44.780 --> 00:33:46.300
so a huge difference.

00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:49.339
And the maximum wait time was unspeakable,

00:33:49.339 --> 00:33:52.260
now less than 10 seconds.

00:33:52.260 --> 00:33:55.260
So 10 seconds is good, but it's not amazing, right?

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:57.660
So can we do better?

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:01.020
We can start our second round of questions

00:34:01.020 --> 00:34:03.579
and just for time reasons, I'm not

00:34:03.579 --> 00:34:05.219
going to show you the profits this time.

00:34:05.219 --> 00:34:06.780
But what it basically shows us is

00:34:06.780 --> 00:34:08.860
that almost all the time you can see

00:34:08.860 --> 00:34:11.699
is in ggplot plotting at this point, several hundred

00:34:11.699 --> 00:34:13.780
milliseconds per plot.

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:16.860
So in order to make this faster, we

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:19.500
now have to turn our attention to optimizing plots.

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:21.899
And that is a particularly difficult thing

00:34:21.899 --> 00:34:24.340
to do for various reasons.

00:34:24.340 --> 00:34:26.260
What we've done with Shiny 1.2 is

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:28.300
introduce this feature called the Quick Query.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:30.260
What we've done with Shiny 1.2 is

00:34:30.260 --> 00:34:32.179
introduce this feature called Plot Caching.

00:34:32.179 --> 00:34:34.580
And if you're not familiar with the concept of caching,

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:36.939
what it means is if you have an operation that

00:34:36.939 --> 00:34:40.500
is going to be performed multiple times with exactly

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:43.260
the same results, maybe don't execute it every time.

00:34:43.260 --> 00:34:45.979
Execute it the first time, save the result,

00:34:45.979 --> 00:34:48.659
and in future times, you recognize that, oh, somebody's

00:34:48.659 --> 00:34:50.620
looking for the same result, and you serve up

00:34:50.620 --> 00:34:53.060
your already cached result.

00:34:53.060 --> 00:34:56.100
So we're going to do exactly this with plots.

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:58.100
It requires Shiny 1.2, so if you want to play with this,

00:34:58.100 --> 00:35:00.820
you'll need to install from CRAN.

00:35:00.820 --> 00:35:03.820
Now, plot caching is not for every Shiny application,

00:35:03.820 --> 00:35:05.280
so there are some criteria you need

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:06.979
to meet before you can decide that this

00:35:06.979 --> 00:35:08.379
is going to work for you.

00:35:08.379 --> 00:35:11.100
Number one, you have to have slow plots.

00:35:11.100 --> 00:35:14.639
If your plots are super fast, then caching them

00:35:14.639 --> 00:35:16.419
is not going to make a huge difference.

00:35:16.419 --> 00:35:17.699
But we do have slow plots.

00:35:17.699 --> 00:35:19.739
There are several hundred milliseconds each.

00:35:19.739 --> 00:35:23.699
And those plots have to be a significant fraction

00:35:23.699 --> 00:35:25.860
of the overall slowness of your app.

00:35:25.979 --> 00:35:28.979
If you're taking seven seconds to load CSV data,

00:35:28.979 --> 00:35:31.419
then speeding up the several hundred milliseconds

00:35:31.419 --> 00:35:33.300
of your plot, you can do it, but it's not

00:35:33.300 --> 00:35:35.100
going to have a dramatic impact.

00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:38.379
But for us, we are highly optimized everywhere else.

00:35:38.379 --> 00:35:42.139
We're just looking at plots remaining.

00:35:42.139 --> 00:35:44.419
Third, and probably most important,

00:35:44.419 --> 00:35:46.860
because caching only speeds things up

00:35:46.860 --> 00:35:50.060
if somebody asks for a plot a second and third and fourth

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:52.340
time, you have to have the kind of app

00:35:52.340 --> 00:35:54.399
where that's going to be likely to happen.

00:35:54.399 --> 00:35:58.320
If everybody's looking at individualized or random data

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:00.760
or data that updates every second,

00:36:00.760 --> 00:36:02.760
then caching may not help you.

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:06.239
But for us, anyone who's looking at a given day

00:36:06.239 --> 00:36:07.879
is looking at the same data.

00:36:07.879 --> 00:36:09.439
So check there as well.

00:36:09.439 --> 00:36:14.080
So we have an excellent candidate for plot caching.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:17.159
Now, we've made this as simple as we possibly can.

00:36:17.159 --> 00:36:19.000
And I'm really proud of the work that

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.800
was done here by Winston Chang.

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:26.000
This is what a regular plot looks like.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:29.080
And this is what it looks like using the new caching feature.

00:36:29.080 --> 00:36:33.919
So number one, we change render plot to render cached plot.

00:36:33.919 --> 00:36:37.159
And number two, it's a little bit trickier to explain,

00:36:37.159 --> 00:36:40.360
but we have to tell Shiny a little bit

00:36:40.360 --> 00:36:42.919
about what are the variables that matter when

00:36:42.919 --> 00:36:44.479
it comes to forming this plot.

00:36:44.479 --> 00:36:47.040
In this particular case, we're plotting diamonds.

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:48.479
We're going to make a scatter plot.

00:36:48.479 --> 00:36:51.719
And we are going to let the user decide what variable

00:36:52.639 --> 00:36:54.120
to set the color.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:56.219
So one user may select Clarity.

00:36:56.219 --> 00:36:58.800
Another one may select Cut.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:03.040
And we need to make sure that we don't mismatch those two

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:04.360
as being equivalent.

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:06.560
So if a user asks for a plot by Clarity,

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:09.800
we don't want to serve them a previously saved version that

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:11.479
was based on Cut.

00:37:11.479 --> 00:37:15.879
So what CacheKey Expert does is it gives you, the Shiny author,

00:37:15.879 --> 00:37:18.719
the opportunity to tell Shiny, when you cache,

00:37:18.719 --> 00:37:20.620
these are the variables that matter.

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:22.340
Now, we are actually doing some things under the hood.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:23.840
Like, if you are on a mobile device,

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:24.840
we'll cache a different version.

00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:26.540
If you're on a retina screen versus not,

00:37:26.540 --> 00:37:27.979
we'll cache a different version.

00:37:27.979 --> 00:37:32.500
We'll actually change it based on the width of your browser.

00:37:32.500 --> 00:37:35.580
But the part that you need to care about is CacheKey Expert.

00:37:35.580 --> 00:37:36.939
But this is all you need to do.

00:37:36.939 --> 00:37:40.219
So I did this seven times for my Shiny app.

00:37:40.219 --> 00:37:43.520
This is the ETL version that we have looked at already.

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:46.100
And once we have made those caching changes

00:37:46.100 --> 00:37:50.139
and run the same test again, holy shit

00:37:50.139 --> 00:37:53.580
is right, there's nothing left.

00:37:53.580 --> 00:37:55.219
There's nothing left that you can see.

00:37:58.939 --> 00:38:02.580
The little rectangles are still there.

00:38:02.580 --> 00:38:04.060
And I can see them on my screen.

00:38:04.060 --> 00:38:07.219
But I guess they're not showing up very well there.

00:38:07.219 --> 00:38:11.780
But the ending point is somewhere around maybe 20

00:38:11.780 --> 00:38:12.300
seconds.

00:38:12.300 --> 00:38:14.020
So this is running significantly faster

00:38:14.020 --> 00:38:17.899
than the original one was with no load at all, which is not

00:38:17.899 --> 00:38:18.860
really that surprising.

00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:20.500
At this point, 20 concurrent users,

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:21.820
what are we even talking about?

00:38:21.820 --> 00:38:23.219
So we are way, way beyond that.

00:38:30.979 --> 00:38:34.780
So again, our original ridiculous version.

00:38:34.780 --> 00:38:36.580
This is ETL.

00:38:36.580 --> 00:38:39.939
And with caching, it's hardly anything to see.

00:38:39.939 --> 00:38:44.659
And I think it's most clear when you look at the latency here.

00:38:44.659 --> 00:38:48.659
That bottom one, I mean, there essentially is no latency.

00:38:48.659 --> 00:38:52.419
Just for fun, I don't have the results here.

00:38:52.419 --> 00:38:53.939
Oh, actually, maybe I do.

00:38:53.939 --> 00:38:56.939
I ran it this morning with 100 concurrent users

00:38:56.939 --> 00:38:58.219
just to see what would happen.

00:38:58.219 --> 00:39:00.620
If we could do all 100 concurrent users that we

00:39:00.620 --> 00:39:02.020
want to support in one process.

00:39:10.739 --> 00:39:12.979
And it is now visible.

00:39:12.979 --> 00:39:16.219
The latency is visible now that we've quintupled the traffic.

00:39:16.260 --> 00:39:19.060
But it is maybe borderline acceptable.

00:39:19.060 --> 00:39:22.020
I'd run maybe two processes with this branch.

00:39:33.100 --> 00:39:36.459
So that kind of summarizes these tools, Shiny Load Test,

00:39:36.459 --> 00:39:38.780
Profvis, and Plot Caching.

00:39:38.780 --> 00:39:40.780
I will make the URL for these slides available.

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:43.459
So if you want to see any of these other URLs,

00:39:43.459 --> 00:39:44.419
you can see it.

00:39:44.419 --> 00:39:47.419
So when I do Q&A, I'll be showing that.

00:39:47.419 --> 00:39:50.340
So with these tools, our goal is to make it much easier

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:52.939
to run Shiny apps in production.

00:39:52.939 --> 00:39:56.260
But these challenges remain, cultural and organizational

00:39:56.260 --> 00:39:57.179
challenges.

00:39:57.179 --> 00:39:59.699
That'd probably be a subject for a pretty good talk.

00:39:59.699 --> 00:40:02.739
But it will not be this talk.

00:40:02.739 --> 00:40:06.340
And finally, I want to leave you with this thought

00:40:06.340 --> 00:40:08.060
that deploying production apps, I

00:40:08.060 --> 00:40:11.820
hope you've gotten the sense that it's a real skill.

00:40:11.860 --> 00:40:16.100
And it takes experience to do this well.

00:40:16.100 --> 00:40:19.620
So be humble when you're deploying production apps.

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:22.739
And especially the people in IT that are haranguing you

00:40:22.739 --> 00:40:28.540
and raising a skeptical eyebrow, they're not the enemy.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:29.659
They might be the enemy.

00:40:29.659 --> 00:40:33.159
But oftentimes, they're not the enemy.

00:40:33.159 --> 00:40:34.739
They have your best interests in mind.

00:40:34.739 --> 00:40:37.459
And they are trying to protect you from pitfalls

00:40:37.459 --> 00:40:41.020
that many, many companies and organizations and programmers

00:40:41.020 --> 00:40:42.820
before you have stumbled into.

00:40:42.820 --> 00:40:47.100
So if you have people in IT and engineering

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:51.020
that you can treat as partners, you're a huge step ahead.

00:40:51.020 --> 00:40:52.860
And definitely lean on those resources

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:55.219
if they're available to you.

00:40:55.219 --> 00:40:58.340
I do want to give credit to the wonderful members

00:40:58.340 --> 00:41:01.899
of the Shiny team, past and present,

00:41:01.899 --> 00:41:04.260
and other members of the RStudio team

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:06.580
who have helped with all the software that I demonstrated

00:41:06.580 --> 00:41:07.540
today.

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:09.820
The Shiny team, I couldn't ask for a better team.

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:11.060
We're really excited about the work

00:41:11.060 --> 00:41:12.139
that we've done in the last couple of years.

00:41:12.139 --> 00:41:14.459
And we're really, really excited about the stuff

00:41:14.459 --> 00:41:16.699
that we're doing this year.

00:41:16.699 --> 00:41:18.979
So thank you.

