Great.

00:41:56.419 --> 00:41:59.820
And with that, I will take seven minutes of questions.

00:41:59.820 --> 00:42:03.020
So if you've been to an RStudio conf before,

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:05.659
you'll know we'll have these throwable microphones.

00:42:05.659 --> 00:42:09.540
And you will also know that I am very poor at throwing.

00:42:09.540 --> 00:42:12.780
So we have a team who will run around

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:13.899
and I'll kind of spot them.

00:42:13.899 --> 00:42:17.419
So Joe can look where you're asking.

00:42:17.419 --> 00:42:19.860
Please remember that a question should

00:42:19.860 --> 00:42:22.860
be a single sentence that ends in a question mark.

00:42:23.219 --> 00:42:24.219
So any questions?

00:42:24.219 --> 00:42:25.219
One over here.

00:42:35.699 --> 00:42:37.860
Talking about the plot caching, is there

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:39.780
a way to do that in a distributed environment

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:43.459
to pass it between multiple servers?

00:42:43.459 --> 00:42:45.419
Is there a way to pass?

00:42:45.419 --> 00:42:45.939
Oh.

00:42:45.939 --> 00:42:47.419
That the cache file on the back is.

00:42:47.419 --> 00:42:49.379
So the question is, is there a way

00:42:49.699 --> 00:42:51.780
Oh, yes.

00:42:51.780 --> 00:42:55.500
So the question is, if you have multiple servers running

00:42:55.500 --> 00:42:57.580
the same Shiny app, can they share the same cache?

00:42:57.580 --> 00:42:59.139
Is that what we're saying?

00:42:59.139 --> 00:42:59.699
Yes.

00:42:59.699 --> 00:43:01.139
OK, great.

00:43:01.139 --> 00:43:01.979
Yes.

00:43:01.979 --> 00:43:07.459
I haven't gone into any detail about where the cached plots

00:43:07.459 --> 00:43:08.580
are being stored.

00:43:08.580 --> 00:43:11.500
But it is an extensible mechanism

00:43:11.500 --> 00:43:14.020
that gives you a lot of control.

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:16.139
So you have several ways to go.

00:43:16.139 --> 00:43:19.739
The simplest way for sort of casual use

00:43:19.739 --> 00:43:22.580
is you can just cache to the file system.

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:26.139
And you could also cache to a shared file system.

00:43:26.139 --> 00:43:28.139
But what I would recommend instead

00:43:28.139 --> 00:43:30.500
is there are examples in the documentation

00:43:30.500 --> 00:43:34.100
for using Redis, which is sort of what all the big boys use

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:35.419
to do this kind of caching.

00:43:35.419 --> 00:43:38.219
Big boys and girls used to do this kind of caching.

00:43:38.219 --> 00:43:41.540
And you can pretty easily plug that in as the back end

00:43:41.540 --> 00:43:43.419
for plot caching.

00:43:43.419 --> 00:43:44.820
Before I take the next question, I

00:43:44.820 --> 00:43:47.139
forgot to point out that this slide deck actually

00:43:47.139 --> 00:43:49.139
has an appendix of best practices.

00:43:49.139 --> 00:43:50.659
By no means complete.

00:43:50.659 --> 00:43:52.500
These are just like the random thoughts

00:43:52.500 --> 00:43:55.020
from my head about some of the different things

00:43:55.020 --> 00:44:00.139
that you might want to do in R to have your apps be

00:44:00.139 --> 00:44:00.979
good production apps.

00:44:05.659 --> 00:44:09.699
You mentioned preparing data in a scheduled R Markdown

00:44:09.699 --> 00:44:10.199
document.

00:44:10.199 --> 00:44:13.739
I'm wondering where you put the files, especially

00:44:13.739 --> 00:44:15.739
on a clustered RConnect environment?

00:44:15.739 --> 00:44:17.860
Yes, great question.

00:44:17.860 --> 00:44:22.699
So currently with Connect, what you would do

00:44:22.699 --> 00:44:25.179
is you would set up a folder somewhere on the I can't,

00:44:25.179 --> 00:44:26.260
I don't know where you are.

00:44:26.260 --> 00:44:27.580
I'm looking in this general direction.

00:44:27.580 --> 00:44:28.739
Sorry if I'm not making eye contact.

00:44:28.739 --> 00:44:29.300
Oh, hi.

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:29.800
Yes.

00:44:32.739 --> 00:44:34.399
With Connect today, what you would do

00:44:34.399 --> 00:44:37.300
is you would create a folder on disk

00:44:37.300 --> 00:44:40.379
that both applications have permissions to access.

00:44:40.379 --> 00:44:43.580
And then you would basically just configure that path

00:44:43.580 --> 00:44:46.379
into your application.

00:44:46.379 --> 00:44:48.179
In the future, what we would really like

00:44:48.179 --> 00:44:53.860
is to have a more sort of first class representation

00:44:53.860 --> 00:44:56.419
of shared data in Connect.

00:44:56.419 --> 00:44:59.860
So the name we've been using for that feature

00:44:59.860 --> 00:45:01.300
is called data pools.

00:45:01.300 --> 00:45:03.620
So unless that changes, if you ever

00:45:03.620 --> 00:45:05.659
see the data pools feature arrive for Connect,

00:45:05.659 --> 00:45:07.000
that's what that's talking about.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:10.060
And that would give us, once we know more

00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:13.300
about what your intent is by having this first class

00:45:13.300 --> 00:45:15.100
feature of a data pool, then we can do things

00:45:15.100 --> 00:45:17.139
like permission the data pool for you

00:45:17.139 --> 00:45:19.340
instead of you having to manage those things yourself.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:21.739
But yes, for today, you could go to a database.

00:45:21.739 --> 00:45:24.340
You could go to a shared file system location.

00:45:24.340 --> 00:45:26.459
But really, you're sort of on your own.

00:45:26.459 --> 00:45:29.179
But there are lots of ways to do it.

00:45:29.179 --> 00:45:31.020
Great question.

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:31.979
Yeah.

00:45:31.979 --> 00:45:33.179
Hi.

00:45:33.179 --> 00:45:37.620
In academia, a lot of credit is based

00:45:37.620 --> 00:45:40.340
on publishing in journals.

00:45:40.340 --> 00:45:43.500
For publishing Shiny apps, do you have a favorite journal?

00:45:43.500 --> 00:45:45.699
Or would you go a different route

00:45:45.699 --> 00:45:49.580
for giving credit to the people making the Shiny apps?

00:45:52.899 --> 00:45:56.459
You should ask anyone else at our studio besides me.

00:45:56.459 --> 00:45:58.620
I barely graduated with a bachelor's.

00:45:58.620 --> 00:46:00.219
So when I hear the word academia,

00:46:00.219 --> 00:46:01.260
I freeze up a little bit.

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:02.179
I have no idea.

00:46:02.179 --> 00:46:04.300
I really don't know anything about journals.

00:46:04.300 --> 00:46:07.939
People ask me, like, I want to cite Shiny.

00:46:07.939 --> 00:46:09.219
How should I cite Shiny?

00:46:09.219 --> 00:46:13.060
And I don't even understand what that question means.

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:14.300
I say cite it however you want.

00:46:14.300 --> 00:46:15.959
And they don't seem to like that answer.

00:46:15.959 --> 00:46:17.659
But I don't know that.

00:46:17.659 --> 00:46:20.780
I honestly don't know.

00:46:20.780 --> 00:46:21.340
Yeah.

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:23.459
Is there anything built or being built

00:46:23.459 --> 00:46:26.580
to help with integration testing, automated integration

00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:27.820
testing for Shiny?

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:32.100
You make me regret that I cut that whole section from my.

00:46:32.100 --> 00:46:34.540
Look at all these hidden slides that I have created.

00:46:41.060 --> 00:46:42.459
Well, I can't.

00:46:42.459 --> 00:46:45.379
Shiny test is the answer to that.

00:46:45.379 --> 00:46:48.699
A Shiny test hit CRAN sometime late last year.

00:46:48.699 --> 00:46:57.179
And what it does is, well, let me preface this by saying,

00:46:57.179 --> 00:46:59.739
you should be unit testing your R code

00:46:59.739 --> 00:47:01.739
that you are calling from your Shiny app.

00:47:01.739 --> 00:47:03.699
But unit testing doesn't help you

00:47:03.699 --> 00:47:06.419
with testing the app as a whole.

00:47:06.419 --> 00:47:09.179
So we call that integration testing.

00:47:09.179 --> 00:47:11.699
Shiny test is specifically designed to help you do that.

00:47:11.699 --> 00:47:14.340
It is designed not only to do integration testing,

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:17.820
but to make it so easy that you might actually do it.

00:47:17.820 --> 00:47:20.780
So what it does is, similar to Shiny load test,

00:47:20.780 --> 00:47:23.780
you record a session of yourself using the app.

00:47:23.780 --> 00:47:28.100
And you have a special UI on the side of your app

00:47:28.100 --> 00:47:31.179
that we inject that lets you say, take a snapshot here,

00:47:31.179 --> 00:47:33.780
take a snapshot here, as you do various things.

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:35.899
And then in the future, as your code changes,

00:47:35.899 --> 00:47:38.500
or as your software configuration changes,

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:42.300
as you upgrade packages from the tidyverse,

00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:44.100
you can run that test again.

00:47:44.100 --> 00:47:45.699
And then it will automatically give you

00:47:45.699 --> 00:47:47.260
a visual view of the differences.

00:47:50.459 --> 00:47:55.020
So sort of like a friendly, not unlike the Git

00:47:55.020 --> 00:47:56.540
support in RStudio.

00:47:56.580 --> 00:48:01.659
So it will give you both sort of a textual representation

00:48:01.659 --> 00:48:03.219
of the data that's different.

00:48:03.219 --> 00:48:07.139
And also, can I show this?

00:48:07.139 --> 00:48:08.219
Nope, I can't show you.

00:48:08.219 --> 00:48:09.739
Ahead and slide.

00:48:09.739 --> 00:48:10.899
OK, let me just.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:17.179
What it'll also do is give you the ability

00:48:17.179 --> 00:48:20.219
to examine, in several different ways,

00:48:20.219 --> 00:48:23.899
the visual snapshot of the before and after your changes.

00:48:23.899 --> 00:48:27.860
So yeah, ShinyTest is where you want to go for that.

00:48:27.860 --> 00:48:28.620
It's 10.30.

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:30.580
One more question?

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:32.060
Yeah, real fast.

00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:34.179
I was just wondering if you all are thinking

00:48:34.179 --> 00:48:36.340
about providing caching for other kinds of rendered

00:48:36.340 --> 00:48:39.419
outputs, leaflet data tables, things like that.

00:48:39.419 --> 00:48:43.139
It is as if I seeded these questions.

00:48:43.139 --> 00:48:46.659
Yes, caching, it's almost backwards

00:48:46.659 --> 00:48:48.300
that we started with plot caching.

00:48:48.300 --> 00:48:50.860
The question is, are there, oh, you guys heard the question.

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:53.379
There's mics.

00:48:53.379 --> 00:48:54.379
It was almost backwards.

00:48:54.379 --> 00:48:56.620
Plot caching is, by far, the hardest thing

00:48:56.620 --> 00:48:59.100
to cache in Shiny.

00:48:59.100 --> 00:49:00.939
So we decided to start there, because that's

00:49:00.939 --> 00:49:05.939
the thing that we don't want users to try to do themselves.

00:49:05.939 --> 00:49:08.540
No offense, but I don't want you to have

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:11.580
to go through that effort to do it correctly.

00:49:11.580 --> 00:49:13.179
Other things are a little bit easier.

00:49:13.179 --> 00:49:14.500
You can kind of build the caching yourself

00:49:14.500 --> 00:49:15.959
if you're sophisticated with Shiny.

00:49:15.959 --> 00:49:19.459
But we were so happy with the way render cache plot turned

00:49:19.459 --> 00:49:23.179
out that what we are investigating

00:49:23.179 --> 00:49:25.820
is there's going to be cache plot,

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:28.379
and then there's going to be everything else cache.

00:49:28.379 --> 00:49:32.860
So there won't be a render cached text or a render

00:49:32.860 --> 00:49:35.340
cached print.

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:37.139
Everything else will get a generic.

00:49:37.139 --> 00:49:40.939
You'll just pipe your render text or whatever

00:49:40.939 --> 00:49:43.300
into a cache directive, and then everything

00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:44.540
will kind of go from there.

00:49:44.540 --> 00:49:46.219
That being said, we're having some kind

00:49:46.260 --> 00:49:51.379
of fierce internal debates about what that API should look like,

00:49:51.379 --> 00:49:54.620
how magic it is, how automatic that cache key expert should

00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:55.659
be.

00:49:55.659 --> 00:49:58.580
So until we sort that out, it's a little bit

00:49:58.580 --> 00:50:00.340
TBD when that feature will land.

00:50:00.340 --> 00:50:04.860
So it's not currently scheduled for a release,

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:07.699
but it's sort of the next natural step.

00:50:07.699 --> 00:50:11.060
But definitely, if you are interested in that,

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:12.760
feel free to file an issue and upvote it,

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:15.100
and that really helps us with our prioritizing.

00:50:15.100 --> 00:50:17.419
Thanks so much.

